\name{compute_likelihood}
\alias{compute_likelihood}
\title{Compute the Likelihood of Data Given Branch Rates}
\description{
Calculates the probability of observing your tip character states given a
phylogenetic tree, a transition rate matrix (Q), and a set of branch-specific
rate scalars. This implements Felsenstein's pruning algorithm, which is the
standard method for computing likelihoods on phylogenies.

\strong{Most users will not need this function directly.} It is used
internally by \code{\link{fitRateScape}} and \code{\link{rateCategories}}.
However, it is exported for users who want to build custom analyses — for
example, computing likelihood profiles, implementing custom MCMC samplers,
or debugging.

Each branch gets its own rate scalar r_i that multiplies the base Q matrix:
the effective rate matrix on branch i is r_i * Q. A rate scalar of 1.0 means
the branch evolves at the baseline rate defined by Q.
}
\usage{
compute_likelihood(tree, data, Q, r_scalars, root_prior = "fitzjohn",
  log_scale = TRUE)
}
\arguments{
\item{tree}{A phylogenetic tree (class \code{"phylo"} from ape).}

\item{data}{A numeric vector of character states at the tips (0-indexed).
Must be in the same order as \code{tree$tip.label}. For a binary trait,
values are 0 and 1. For k states, values are 0 to k-1.}

\item{Q}{A transition rate matrix (k x k) from \code{\link{makeQ}()}.}

\item{r_scalars}{A numeric vector of rate multipliers, one per edge (branch).
Length must equal \code{nrow(tree$edge)}. A value of 1.0 means the branch
evolves at the baseline rate.}

\item{root_prior}{How to handle the root state. Same options as
\code{\link{fitRateScape}}: \code{"fitzjohn"} (default), \code{"equal"},
or \code{"stationary"}.}

\item{log_scale}{If \code{TRUE} (default), returns the log-likelihood.
Log-likelihoods are numerically more stable and are what the MCMC sampler
